Here's the complete migration:

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wakes on either a new event OR cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            List<string> items;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                items = new List<string>(_queue);
                _queue.Clear();
            }

            foreach (var item in items)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) and throws `ThreadInterruptedException`. Cancelling the token signals `token.WaitHandle`, which unblocks `WaitAny`. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). Cooperative cancellation makes it unnecessary. |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop exits voluntarily when cancellation is requested. |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)` | Waits on **both** the event and the cancellation token's wait handle, so the thread wakes for either new work or shutdown. |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter-weight; avoids kernel-mode transition for short waits. |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` added | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEventSlim` must be disposed to avoid timer/handle leaks. |

## Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`WaitOne()` without token** — If you keep the original `_newEvent.WaitOne()`, `_cts.Cancel()` will **not** unblock it. You must use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle`.

2. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks. Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`.

3. **Cancellation isn't immediate** — The thread only exits at the next `WaitAny` or loop iteration. If `Handle(item)` is long-running, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` checkpoints inside it.

4. **Queue drain race** — The original code dequeued one item per signal. If `Enqueue` is called twice before `WaitOne` returns, the second item sits until another signal. The migrated version drains all items each wake-up.

5. **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — If you convert `Handle()` to be cancellation-aware, let `OperationCanceledException` propagate out of `RunLoop` naturally rather than catching and ignoring it.
